Denote by $h$ the height tru $ABC$ from $A$ to $BC$. So triangle $ABC$ is said to have area$\frac{1}{2} \cdot BC \cdot h$. Triangle $ABC$ has equal base length and height, hence its area is $r^2/2$. Using Pythagoras on $ABC$, we get
\begin{align*} h^2 = 1^2 - r^2 \\\\ \frac{r^2}{2} = \frac{1^2 + r^2}{2} - r^2\end{align*}
Conclusion is that $r = \sqrt{2}$. So if you plug this value of $r$ into the area of triangle $ACE$ right here, you'll get $\frac{28}{9}$, which is 70\% of the area of the hexagon, so we can conclude that the answer is $ \sqrt{2}$. </think> $\boxed{149}$

